6
00:00:20,048 --> 00:00:21,085
Only 2 more to go.

7
00:00:22,054 --> 00:00:25,048
These probably date back to the '50s.
Don't make 'em like this anymore.

8
00:00:25,168 --> 00:00:26,906
Which is why we're replacing them.

9
00:00:27,026 --> 00:00:28,509
It's an out-of-date design.

10
00:00:28,777 --> 00:00:30,011
Just like your haircut.

11
00:00:32,040 --> 00:00:33,056
What is that?

12
00:00:33,648 --> 00:00:34,850
I don't know.

13
00:00:36,919 --> 00:00:38,186
I thought this one was empty.

14
00:00:38,306 --> 00:00:39,762
It's supposed to be.

15
00:00:46,134 --> 00:00:47,214
No way.

16
00:00:50,445 --> 00:00:52,084
- Did you get it?
- Yeah. Hand it over.

17
00:00:52,299 --> 00:00:53,903
Come on, come on, come on.

18
00:00:56,816 --> 00:00:58,289
Double shot vin-spresso.

19
00:00:58,409 --> 00:00:59,373
Do not tell him.

20
00:00:59,780 --> 00:01:01,167
Not if he tortured me.

21
00:01:04,054 --> 00:01:05,054
Nice try.

22
00:01:05,645 --> 00:01:06,547
Dad, come on.

23
00:01:06,667 --> 00:01:07,699
No, a dozen.

24
00:01:09,043 --> 00:01:10,465
Long. Long-stemmed.

25
00:01:11,383 --> 00:01:12,386
Okay, thanks.

26
00:01:14,051 --> 00:01:16,842
- Who are the flowers for?
- None of your business. This...

27
00:01:17,560 --> 00:01:18,601
Is Vincent's coffee.

28
00:01:18,856 --> 00:01:20,603
Vincent knows not to supply...

29
00:01:21,925 --> 00:01:22,925
You.

30
00:01:28,022 --> 00:01:29,566
You have a middleman.

31
00:01:34,577 --> 00:01:35,868
You'll never break me.

32
00:01:46,475 --> 00:01:48,756
"Sassy pumps for fall."

33
00:01:52,720 --> 00:01:54,076
I'm so ashamed.

34
00:01:54,893 --> 00:01:56,138
Dealing to minors.

35
00:01:56,270 --> 00:01:57,890
Coffee's not a drug, Dad.

36
00:01:58,029 --> 00:02:00,846
Then, you can quit whenever you want,
no driving lessons until you do.

37
00:02:00,981 --> 00:02:01,981
- But...
- Ah.

38
00:02:02,322 --> 00:02:03,270
No buts.

39
00:02:04,032 --> 00:02:05,965
I love you too much to watch you...

40
00:02:06,371 --> 00:02:07,837
do this to yourself.

41
00:02:12,881 --> 00:02:14,490
Sure. It's Allison.

42
00:02:18,104 --> 00:02:19,161
Jack Carter.

43
00:02:19,318 --> 00:02:20,662
Oh, hey. It's me.

44
00:02:20,784 --> 00:02:21,829
Yeah.

45
00:02:22,882 --> 00:02:25,000
Okay... Well, we have a bit of

46
00:02:25,122 --> 00:02:26,869
<i>an unusual situation up here.</i>

47
00:02:26,989 --> 00:02:29,004
Oh, at Global Dynamics? Imagine.

48
00:02:29,164 --> 00:02:32,122
Well, this one's unprecedented,
even for us.

49
00:02:32,428 --> 00:02:33,633
<i>What do you want me to do...</i>

50
00:02:34,172 --> 00:02:35,177
Evacuate the town?

51
00:02:35,521 --> 00:02:38,426
Okay, I get it. You're still mad at me.
How long are you gonna punish

52
00:02:38,552 --> 00:02:39,552
<i>me for this?</i>

53
00:02:42,028 --> 00:02:44,352
I'm just trying to do my job.
I'll be there shortly.

54
00:02:48,986 --> 00:02:50,066
What was that about?

55
00:02:50,256 --> 00:02:51,715
Nothing... Gotta go.

56
00:02:51,842 --> 00:02:53,236
We'll talk consequences later.

57
00:02:54,979 --> 00:02:56,615
- Can't wait.
- Can't wait.

58
00:03:00,074 --> 00:03:01,194
He broke me like a stick.

59
00:03:01,319 --> 00:03:03,389
Which will make revenge
that much sweeter.

60
00:03:03,566 --> 00:03:04,822
He left his cell phone.

61
00:03:04,950 --> 00:03:06,184
What are you gonna do?

62
00:03:06,424 --> 00:03:08,505
I don't know...
Getting as much coffee and

63
00:03:08,639 --> 00:03:10,628
driving lessons as I want.

64
00:03:13,563 --> 00:03:16,384
Hi, yes. I'm calling for my boss,
Jack Carter.

65
00:03:16,506 --> 00:03:18,134
I believe he just ordered flowers.

66
00:03:18,570 --> 00:03:21,347
Right, well, I just needed to verify
the spelling of the name?

67
00:03:22,492 --> 00:03:23,698
Okay. Yeah, that's...

68
00:03:23,853 --> 00:03:25,002
That's right. Thank you.

69
00:03:29,504 --> 00:03:31,460
Who the hell is Angela Fairfield?

70
00:03:33,173 --> 00:03:35,236
<i>Okay, Carter. Can we talk about this?</i>

71
00:03:38,748 --> 00:03:39,748
I don't...

72
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:42,985
I don't know what to say.

73
00:03:43,463 --> 00:03:45,939
I mean, you withheld information

74
00:03:46,094 --> 00:03:49,099
that Stark's device could be
causing the shared dreaming.

75
00:03:49,289 --> 00:03:50,710
I apologized for that.

76
00:03:50,898 --> 00:03:53,004
Allison, I'm just gonna
be mad for a while.

77
00:03:54,675 --> 00:03:55,675
Okay?

78
00:03:58,114 --> 00:03:59,114
Okay.

79
00:04:03,304 --> 00:04:04,948
So, what's the emergency?

80
00:04:05,423 --> 00:04:07,410
We're updating the equipment
in cryogenics.

81
00:04:07,649 --> 00:04:08,512
Thank god.

82
00:04:08,632 --> 00:04:11,729
A number of people have elected
to go into cryostasis over the years,

83
00:04:11,865 --> 00:04:13,441
going back to the 1950s.

84
00:04:13,563 --> 00:04:14,707
Cryostasis?

85
00:04:15,023 --> 00:04:16,032
Cold stored?

86
00:04:16,232 --> 00:04:17,733
To be revived at a later date,

87
00:04:17,889 --> 00:04:19,293
ideally after we found the cure

88
00:04:19,427 --> 00:04:21,160
for whatever disease
they were dying from.

89
00:04:21,293 --> 00:04:24,127
Creepy, yes. But I don't think
that falls under my jurisdiction.

90
00:04:24,266 --> 00:04:26,640
Well, we discovered a person
in an unmarked chamber,

91
00:04:26,795 --> 00:04:28,164
a very old chamber.

92
00:04:28,491 --> 00:04:30,888
Okay, so GD put some food
in the freezer without labeling it,

93
00:04:31,019 --> 00:04:33,154
now it's mystery meat.
Seems like an internal problem.

94
00:04:33,287 --> 00:04:35,157
There's a little more
to it than that, Carter.

95
00:04:35,424 --> 00:04:37,862
Like, the fact that this one
has a heartbeat.

96
00:04:46,006 --> 00:04:47,072
What's he doing here?

97
00:04:47,228 --> 00:04:49,059
Nathan's early research
was in cryogenics.

98
00:04:49,499 --> 00:04:51,218
- Of course it was.
- How's it going?

99
00:04:51,351 --> 00:04:52,954
We are monitoring the defrost rate.

100
00:04:53,074 --> 00:04:55,777
Opening the chambers too quickly
could destabilize his tissues.

101
00:04:56,005 --> 00:04:58,021
I can't believe this is happening
in my lifetime...

102
00:04:58,164 --> 00:05:00,395
- Right here, right now.
- Fargo, don't hurt yourself.

103
00:05:00,515 --> 00:05:01,572
No, you don't understand.

104
00:05:01,783 --> 00:05:03,007
This is history in the making.

105
00:05:03,142 --> 00:05:05,325
The first person ever
to come out of cryostasis alive.

106
00:05:05,448 --> 00:05:06,452
His pulse is dropping.

107
00:05:06,725 --> 00:05:08,078
We gotta get him out of there.

108
00:05:08,201 --> 00:05:10,249
I need all medical personnel
standing by.

109
00:05:15,260 --> 00:05:17,087
- Ready to make history?
- Hit it.

110
00:05:21,752 --> 00:05:24,481
- Why is he standing backwards?
- why is he fully clothed?

111
00:05:24,706 --> 00:05:28,682
His pulse is slow, but stable.
His vital signs look strong.

112
00:05:29,341 --> 00:05:30,434
Okay, get him out of there.

113
00:05:32,684 --> 00:05:33,684
Gently.

114
00:05:34,203 --> 00:05:35,209
Ready?

115
00:05:35,332 --> 00:05:36,338
Lift him up.

116
00:05:37,793 --> 00:05:39,609
We need to get him up to the infirmary.

117
00:05:41,298 --> 00:05:42,112
Hold on.

118
00:05:45,113 --> 00:05:46,575
Pierre Fargo.

119
00:05:52,970 --> 00:05:53,970
Grampa?

120
00:05:58,562 --> 00:06:01,676
The Projet-SG Team
<i>presents:</i>

121
00:06:05,883 --> 00:06:08,070
<i>Timing:</i>   Golgi,
Linwelin, Moochie, Ricana.

122
00:06:08,489 --> 00:06:10,604
<i>Transcript:</i>   swsub.com

