00:06:17,081 --> 00:06:19,820
<i>Proofreading:</i>   Golgi, Linwelin.

125
00:06:22,644 --> 00:06:25,408
- Season 2 | Episode 7 -
Family Reunion (v. 1.0)

126
00:06:35,497 --> 00:06:36,875
All my life, I thought he ran out

127
00:06:36,998 --> 00:06:39,315
on my grandma,
and he's been right here all along.

128
00:06:39,794 --> 00:06:41,671
Of all the people
to bring out of cryostasis,

129
00:06:41,795 --> 00:06:43,562
I resurrect another Fargo.

130
00:06:44,297 --> 00:06:45,392
Karma's a bitch.

131
00:06:46,675 --> 00:06:47,989
Is anyone curious

132
00:06:48,171 --> 00:06:50,138
as to how
he got in there?

133
00:06:50,261 --> 00:06:51,306
He's a Fargo.

134
00:06:51,527 --> 00:06:52,682
Are you really surprised?

135
00:06:52,806 --> 00:06:54,017
I am standing right here.

136
00:06:54,140 --> 00:06:55,283
He just twitched.

137
00:06:55,421 --> 00:06:56,853
I think he
might've heard you.

138
00:06:56,976 --> 00:06:57,984
Belle...

139
00:06:59,020 --> 00:07:00,383
I'm Allison Blake.

140
00:07:01,115 --> 00:07:02,400
Do you know
your name?

141
00:07:02,524 --> 00:07:03,767
Everyone knows my name.

142
00:07:03,890 --> 00:07:04,902
I'm Pierre Fargo.

143
00:07:05,610 --> 00:07:07,070
The Pierre Fargo.

144
00:07:07,195 --> 00:07:08,573
Do you know the date, Pierre?

145
00:07:08,697 --> 00:07:11,580
I prefer Dr. Fargo,
thank you.

146
00:07:11,917 --> 00:07:14,203
And yes,
it's august 30th, 1957.

147
00:07:15,166 --> 00:07:16,716
Did I hit my head or something?

148
00:07:17,038 --> 00:07:18,338
You're at
Global Dynamics.

149
00:07:18,478 --> 00:07:19,478
You've...

150
00:07:19,851 --> 00:07:21,002
been asleep for a while.

151
00:07:21,126 --> 00:07:23,671
Does anyone
know the time? Because

152
00:07:23,795 --> 00:07:26,523
my girl Belle and I have
dinner plans, and I can't be late.

153
00:07:26,712 --> 00:07:28,262
I don't know how to say this...

154
00:07:29,008 --> 00:07:30,138
You're already late.

155
00:07:30,701 --> 00:07:32,304
Like 50 years late.

156
00:07:32,629 --> 00:07:34,473
- Excuse me?
- Pierre...

157
00:07:34,597 --> 00:07:36,225
You just woke up from cryostasis.

158
00:07:37,587 --> 00:07:38,436
Sure I did.

159
00:07:38,719 --> 00:07:40,749
I know this may be
difficult to process...

160
00:07:40,896 --> 00:07:44,122
But you've been
in cryostasis since 1957.

161
00:07:44,268 --> 00:07:46,214
The year is 2007.

162
00:07:46,529 --> 00:07:47,717
No way you're convincing me

163
00:07:47,918 --> 00:07:50,374
that I just woke up
50 years in the future.

164
00:07:52,081 --> 00:07:53,284
Put your glasses on.

165
00:07:55,034 --> 00:07:56,030
Okay.

166
00:07:59,168 --> 00:08:00,271
That's better.

167
00:08:17,127 --> 00:08:18,420
Do I know you?

168
00:08:18,767 --> 00:08:20,090
I'm Douglas Fargo.

169
00:08:20,614 --> 00:08:21,814
I'm your grandson.

170
00:08:26,491 --> 00:08:29,444
Imagine waking up and
everything you know is gone.

171
00:08:29,860 --> 00:08:31,581
Nathan's gonna keep him
under observation

172
00:08:31,701 --> 00:08:33,282
until we're sure that he's stabilized.

173
00:08:33,792 --> 00:08:35,334
Cryogenics to babysitting?

174
00:08:36,014 --> 00:08:37,502
- Sheriff Carter?
- Yeah.

175
00:08:37,725 --> 00:08:38,770
How you doing?

176
00:08:38,897 --> 00:08:40,330
Um, better than my granddad.

177
00:08:40,455 --> 00:08:42,499
Listen, I know Fargos have

178
00:08:42,638 --> 00:08:45,127
a reputation for being
in the wrong place at the wrong time,

179
00:08:45,378 --> 00:08:47,496
but if he says
he doesn't know how he got

180
00:08:47,652 --> 00:08:49,673
into that chamber, I believe him.

181
00:08:49,934 --> 00:08:51,680
Maybe somebody put him in there.

182
00:08:51,800 --> 00:08:54,469
The same way somebody put you
into the force field bubble?

183
00:08:54,874 --> 00:08:56,129
Okay, fair point.

184
00:08:56,582 --> 00:08:57,931
But we're not talking about me.

185
00:08:58,678 --> 00:08:59,669
Fargos may be cursed,

186
00:08:59,854 --> 00:09:01,077
but we're honest.

187
00:09:01,335 --> 00:09:03,202
Will you please just look into it?

188
00:09:03,734 --> 00:09:06,022
I'll personally put someone
on that right away.

189
00:09:09,332 --> 00:09:11,693
I'm sorry, is... Is my working

190
00:09:11,849 --> 00:09:13,094
disturbing your reading?

191
00:09:13,792 --> 00:09:14,792
No.

192
00:09:18,928 --> 00:09:20,333
So does Allison know?

193
00:09:20,669 --> 00:09:21,669
About?

194
00:09:21,955 --> 00:09:23,957
The woman you're sending flowers to.

195
00:09:24,082 --> 00:09:25,347
It's none of Allison's business,

196
00:09:25,503 --> 00:09:26,710
nor do I think she would care.

197
00:09:28,758 --> 00:09:30,543
Did something happen with you two?

198
00:09:30,677 --> 00:09:32,975
- Could we talk about something else?
- Like what?

199
00:09:33,232 --> 00:09:34,217
Like what...

200
00:09:34,403 --> 00:09:36,344
Pumps are gonna be in fashion this fall?

201
00:09:36,582 --> 00:09:39,305
I'm just asking, 'cause
I wanna know what belts to buy.

202
00:09:41,204 --> 00:09:42,022
Funny.

203
00:09:46,215 --> 00:09:48,231
Pierre was working with Andre Sandrov.

204
00:09:49,290 --> 00:09:51,067
- Who is...?
- Who is

205
00:09:51,192 --> 00:09:54,070
- Eureka's Albert Einstein?
- I would have thought

206
00:09:54,195 --> 00:09:56,828
Albert Einstein would have been
Eureka's Albert Einstein.

207
00:09:57,018 --> 00:09:58,041
Yeah, but

208
00:09:58,187 --> 00:10:01,040
point is, Sandrov's revered.
By everyone.

209
00:10:01,550 --> 00:10:04,305
And he gave a statement
that Pierre went awol

210
00:10:04,425 --> 00:10:05,920
in 1957

211
00:10:06,040 --> 00:10:08,506
after giving written notice at work.

212
00:10:08,626 --> 00:10:10,884
Which Pierre didn't mention.

213
00:10:12,682 --> 00:10:15,443
The cold war's over,
the Soviet Union is gone,

214
00:10:15,594 --> 00:10:17,043
the Red Sox won the World Series.

215
00:10:17,166 --> 00:10:20,090
Don't understand why that was important,
but everybody tell me it is.

216
00:10:20,214 --> 00:10:22,045
I just don't really get baseba...

217
00:10:22,178 --> 00:10:23,634
Grampa, are you listening?

218
00:10:23,768 --> 00:10:25,134
Hey, look...

219
00:10:26,734 --> 00:10:29,566
I'm having a hard time
processing all of this, okay?

220
00:10:29,689 --> 00:10:31,839
And you seem like a really nice guy.

221
00:10:31,991 --> 00:10:35,097
And I admit that there's
a slight resemblance. But, you know...

222
00:10:35,256 --> 00:10:37,175
This is insane. I'm Pierre Fargo.

223
00:10:37,424 --> 00:10:38,941
I'm nobody's grampa.

224
00:10:39,133 --> 00:10:41,224
Okay? I'm not even a father.

225
00:10:41,540 --> 00:10:43,096
I'm pretty sure you were.

226
00:10:45,706 --> 00:10:47,510
Look, we're practically the same age.

227
00:10:47,852 --> 00:10:49,301
Well, yeah, pretty much.

228
00:10:49,424 --> 00:10:52,753
Okay, great. So in light of that,
let's just drop "grampa"

229
00:10:52,972 --> 00:10:55,391
and stick with "Dr. Fargo." Okay?

230
00:10:55,924 --> 00:10:57,223
Nice meeting you.

231
00:10:58,491 --> 00:10:59,491
Wait!

232
00:11:00,388 --> 00:11:02,096
Wait, wait!

233
00:11:02,677 --> 00:11:04,652
Belle St. John is my grandmother.

234
00:11:05,427 --> 00:11:07,615
- So Belle is still alive?
- Very much so.

235
00:11:08,178 --> 00:11:09,818
Well, that's wonderful news.

236
00:11:10,108 --> 00:11:11,148
I have to see her.

237
00:11:11,271 --> 00:11:13,530
- How do you get out of here?
- Not by going that way.

238
00:11:13,650 --> 00:11:15,053
You can't see her. She's in Alaska.

239
00:11:15,173 --> 00:11:17,365
Which, is a state now.
It's very big with tourists.

240
00:11:17,485 --> 00:11:19,294
- What's she doing there?
- No, not that way.

241
00:11:19,428 --> 00:11:22,114
She's dogsledding.
She'll be back on the weekend.

242
00:11:22,239 --> 00:11:25,419
- My Belle always had a wild side.
- She also had a son.

243
00:11:26,361 --> 00:11:27,836
My dad, Thomas.

244
00:11:28,110 --> 00:11:30,588
He died in a lab accident
when I was a little kid.

245
00:11:31,090 --> 00:11:32,340
Pushed the wrong button.

246
00:11:32,798 --> 00:11:33,967
I'm sorry to hear that.

247
00:11:35,395 --> 00:11:37,800
So I suppose
she must've gotten married, then,

248
00:11:37,951 --> 00:11:39,472
- If she had a son.
- No.

249
00:11:40,028 --> 00:11:42,556
She always said she was
holding out for her dream man.

250
00:11:43,172 --> 00:11:44,219
Really?

251
00:11:45,276 --> 00:11:47,028
I brought a picture of her.

252
00:11:47,818 --> 00:11:50,969
Might look a little bit different
than she did when she was 20.

253
00:11:55,947 --> 00:11:57,587
She's still beautiful.

254
00:11:58,987 --> 00:12:00,375
I've missed so much.

255
00:12:02,535 --> 00:12:04,122
But I'm not missing any more.

256
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:06,958
<i>1957</i>

257
00:12:07,078 --> 00:12:08,501
brand new Ford Thunderbirds

258
00:12:08,835 --> 00:12:10,461
cost 3,000 bucks.

259
00:12:10,581 --> 00:12:13,131
Speaking of cars,
I'd like to start driving mine.

260
00:12:13,501 --> 00:12:14,716
Not 'till you dry out.

261
00:12:15,383 --> 00:12:17,385
- I haven't had caffeine all day.
- I said a week.

262
00:12:17,980 --> 00:12:19,019
A week.

263
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:21,804
Wanna play hardball?

